title: For Sale:  Mid-90s Crosman 1389 Backpacker converted to 22cal. $175 obo
postcontent:
This was originally a .17cal 1389 backpacker I purchased at Walmart sometime between 1995-1996.
I started the conversion in 2013.  It is .22cal now...assembled and fully functioning...hits hard...as fun
as it gets.  Sorry, no chrony numbers, I don't have one and couldn't quite get phone/tablet software
chrony to work indoors.

From all I've learned while working on this project, I honestly believe this setup can produce
...in the ballpark of...650-700 fps with 14.3g pellets at 15-20 pumps...13-15 fpe.
It currently has a combination of new/original valve internals, ie: check valve, valve stem and spring,
with no threads cut off of the original brass valve in an effort to target a "low volume-high pressure,
14 inch barrel" system.  It fully dumps 20 pumps.

In the right home, this multi-pumper could still benefit from some minor work and tweaking.
I'm just going in a different direction to find a solution for a bugout bag protein gitter.

I'm probably wrong, but, it seems that everything I'm including in this sale is merely one purchase away
from two entire pellet guns, would need 2nd grip/frame with trigger internals...last time I checked $25
http://alliancehobby.com/gripframe.htm

Individual dollar amounts, shown below, added up = $262

As .22cal it now includes:

-Original Backpacker shoulder stock with original "fat" forend, green ($25 value?)
-Original rear-cocking system that work ever so nicely...can carry loaded and not pumped/cocked.
   (no longer available anywhere?...$30 value?)

   (sweet, smooth, crisp trigger)
-Original brass valve, flattened and ported by Mellonair, (brass no longer available anywhere? (*)

-New steel pivot pin, replacing the original rolled steel pin, with brass nuts and spacer
   in middle of pump lever (Mellonair (*).
-New Crosman .22cal, 14" barrel ($40...my first and only Ebay WIN!)
-New aluminum breech from Alliancehobby, left side bolt, 2 x barrel set screws,
   accommodates plastic rear site, grooved for scope mount, accepts/uses 2-piece bolt ($60)

 ($30, shipped with all internals including pump arm, etc...all unused parts included in spare parts)
-New ice cube maker poly tubing transfer port.
-New brass screws/nuts on forend. ($2)
-New NCStar 4x20 scope ($10)
(*) I spent roughly $50 to get: Mellonair flat-top piston, flatten and port my original brass valve,
steel pass-through bolt and steel pivot-pin/brass nuts.

Spare parts included in sale and not used in current setup (I'm sure I probably left something out,
but will include every last part/piece I have):

---original "1389 Backpacker" main tube, nicely polished inside, stored 15 yrs with one (maybe two)

---original barrel spacer
---original .17cal steel breech including all screws
---original 14 inch .17cal barrel including little steel bushing that fits barrel into breech,
    still nicely rifled and no rust
---original .17cal swing-out pellet bung (in great shape)
---original and new steel transfer ports with original rubber grommet/seal
---original and new plastic pistons/cups
---new .22cal swing-out pellet bung ($15, Alliancehobby, purchased before I found direction of project,
    currently not being used because of the new aluminum breech with bolt)
---new pump arm hardware including new thin-style forend (black)
---.22cal steel pass-through bolt from Mellonair (needs some work to function with left-side bolt *)
---various proprietary screws, couple allen wrenches, roll pins for pivot and forend, etc.
---tin of Crosman Premier Hollow Points, 14.3g, approx. 450 of em.

This rifle falls into the "ghost" serial range of Model 94's that lies between approx. serial 2586000 and 2700000. These numbers were not all filled and this range marks the end of Pre 64 Winchester Model 94 production. To find any original model 94 in this range is a collector's prize. Please check out Robert Renneberg's fine book THE WINCHESTER MODEL 94 2nd edition, page 36 for additional information regarding this mysterious serial block of 94 and their rarity. This particular example is in MINT nearly new perhaps unfired outside the facory condition. Perfect screw, mint bore and nearly no wear or handling marks. We rate it at 99% and all original. It could be one of the very LAST Pre-64 Model 94's ever made. It cannot be upgraded with regards to original condition or rarity.....Please note that I am not an FFL dealer and can only ship to FFL dealers. Sorry, don't mean to be rude, but you'd be AMAZED as to the emails I've received trying to sell this optic. It's like a soap opera. This is a GREAT deal for someone who wants a rugged, accurate, and fast site. It's priced $100 lower than a new one (being only a month or two old).

The pictures are stock photos, but I can send you a photo of mine too if that's critical for your decision. Thanks!

From Aimpoint:

"Aimpoint PRO Patrol Rifle Optic 12841: Designed with input from a distinguished group of current and former professionals, the Patrol Rifle Optic incorporates many never before seen features to maximize this sight's performance within the challenging conditions faced by modern law enforcement. A hard-anodized 30mm tube was utilized, enclosing a high efficiency circuit that allows the sight to be turned on and left on for up to three years using a single battery. The Aimpoint PRO Patrol Rifle Optic's front lens utilizes a unique band-pass coating, which allows the sight to be used with all generations of night vision devices. The modular QRP2 mount includes a removable spacer that indexes the sight at the optimal height for co-witness with the standard iron sights on AR15/M16/M4 Carbine style weapons. This spacer can be removed to enable the use of the sight on police shotguns or sub-machine guns. The QRP2 mount for the PRO Optic also incorporates a torque-limiting twist knob that provides the optimal level of pressure on the rail while completely eliminating the possibility of over-tightening. Both the PRO Optic's front and rear lenses are recessed within the sight body to provide protection against impact damage, scratches and fingerprints."
